            "answer_text": "Un-policed over reliance on community moderation.  (I haven't seen that happen here.) Reddit, Wikipedia and other sites have all had this problem as well as Yahoo! answers. Community moderation will eventually lead to self selected tinpot dictators who end up controlling content according to their worldviews.  Misogyny often accompanies this and it drives off anyone who disagrees. It works like this:  First, everyone participates and there is camaraderie.  Gradually, people who are motivated by control gain power because they want to \"fix\" things.  They are inflexible tend to make things miserable for people they disagree with.  Over time, the site sees more and more of these people until they pretty much control things.   Wikipedia is the poster child for this.  Their base of editors is pretty low and it's because anyone new who tries to edit has to get past a bunch of controlling jerks. At that point, they've driven away most of the talented people because they are the first to have trouble with the control freaks.   ",
